<subSubSection lastPageId="27" lastPageNumber="28" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="26.[151,1436,1864,2010]" lastBlockId="27.[151,1436,152,498]" lastPageId="27" lastPageNumber="28" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,281,1864,1890]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
Male with dark brown hairs on all femora. Phallus (
<figureCitation box="[899,969,1864,1890]" captionStart="FIGURES 7 – 11" captionStartId="9.[151,269,1761,1785]" captionTargetBox="[155,1430,197,1734]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[155,1432,197,1735]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 7 – 11. Inner male genitalia (phallus). 7. C. decorus; 8. C. spurius; 9. C. zyginae; 10. C. griseus; 11. Chalarus sp. near zyginae. Scale bars = 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/184952/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">
Fig. 
<number box="[954,969,1864,1890]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" value="9.0">9</number>
</figureCitation>
) with phs straight; tdp short and broad; Lmtdp:Ltdp~ 
<number box="[312,349,1904,1930]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" value="2.7">2.7</number>
; two php which are app. as long as mtdp; all ejaculatory ducts placed distally on mtdp; ejaculatory apodeme parasol-shaped (as in 
<figureCitation box="[605,690,1944,1970]" captionStart="FIGURES 12 – 23" captionStartId="10.[151,269,1761,1785]" captionTargetBox="[155,1431,197,1734]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[155,1432,197,1734]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 12 – 23. Figs 12 – 15. Inner male genitalia (phallus). 12. C. marki spec. nov.; 13. C. indistinctus; 14. C. brevicuadis; 15. C. longicaudis. Figs 16 – 23. Ejaculatory apodeme of male. 16. C. juliae; 17. C. latifrons; 18. C. absconditus spec. nov.; – 19. C. griseus; – 20. C. saxonicus spec. nov.; 21. C. spurius; 22. C. immanis spec. nov.; 23. C. marki spec. nov. Scale bars = 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/184953/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">
Fig. 
<number box="[658,690,1944,1970]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" value="19.0">19</number>
</figureCitation>
); Female with frontal facets greatly enlarged (as in J 
<number box="[1300,1331,1944,1970]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" value="92.0">92</number>
<figureCitation box="[1331,1396,1944,1970]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 6" captionStartId="7.[151,269,1761,1785]" captionTargetBox="[155,1430,197,1734]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[155,1432,197,1735]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 6. Inner male genitalia (phallus). 1. C. fimbriatus agg.; 2. C. absconditus spec. nov.; 3. C. clarus; 4. C. immanis spec. nov.; 5. C. juliae; Abbreviations: lower ej. d., lower ejaculatory ductuli; mtdp, membranous tip of distiphallus; php, phallic processes; phs, phallic shaft; tdp, tip of distiphallus; upper ej. d., upper ejaculatory duct; 6. C. latifrons. Scale bars = 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/184951/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">
Fig. 
<number box="[1382,1396,1944,1970]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
D); frons very narrow, at narrowest point 1.0 times diameter of largest frontal facet; flagellum dark brown; legs dark brown but base of femora and area around femoral-tibial joints may be somewhat paler; pulvilli of all legs of same size, shorter than distitarsus; hairs on femora mid to dark brown but pvsr of mid femur light brown; hairs on thorax and abdomen dark brown; abdominal tergites dark brown; ovipositor as in 
<figureCitation box="[1298,1433,232,258]" captionStart="FIGURES 49 – 62" captionStartId="14.[151,269,1908,1932]" captionTargetBox="[159,1427,429,1881]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[155,1432,425,1882]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURES 49 – 62. Female ovipositor. 49 – 50. C. holosericeus lateral view; Abbreviation: s 9, sternite 9; 51 – 52. C. zyginae lateral view; 53. C. exiguus lateral view; 54. C. saxonicus spec. nov. dorsal view; 55. C. saxonicus spec. nov. lateral view; 56. C. exiguus dorsal view; 57. C. holosericeus dorsal view; 58. C. griseus lateral view; 59. C. clarus lateral view; 60. C. proprius dorsal view; 61 – 62. C. proprius lateral view. Scale bars = 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/184956/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">
Figs 
<number box="[1355,1433,232,258]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" value="51.5" valueMax="52.0" valueMin="51.0">51–52</number>
</figureCitation>
. See Table 
<number box="[272,287,272,298]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" value="1.0">1</number>
for coxI and ITS 
<number box="[489,503,272,298]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" value="2.0">2</number>
barcode sequence accession numbers.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="27.[151,1436,152,498]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,360,311,337]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Annotations:</emphasis>
<collectionCode LSID="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15536" box="[371,435,312,338]" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15536" name="Department of Natural Resources, Environment, The Arts and Sport" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">DNA</collectionCode>
barcodes could be obtained for males only. The female 
<typeStatus box="[1120,1222,312,338]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">holotype</typeStatus>
was studied. The ovipositor is figured in 
<figureCitation box="[428,514,352,378]" captionStart="FIGURES 49 – 62" captionStartId="14.[151,269,1908,1932]" captionTargetBox="[159,1427,429,1881]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[155,1432,425,1882]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURES 49 – 62. Female ovipositor. 49 – 50. C. holosericeus lateral view; Abbreviation: s 9, sternite 9; 51 – 52. C. zyginae lateral view; 53. C. exiguus lateral view; 54. C. saxonicus spec. nov. dorsal view; 55. C. saxonicus spec. nov. lateral view; 56. C. exiguus dorsal view; 57. C. holosericeus dorsal view; 58. C. griseus lateral view; 59. C. clarus lateral view; 60. C. proprius dorsal view; 61 – 62. C. proprius lateral view. Scale bars = 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/184956/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">
Fig. 
<number box="[483,514,352,378]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" value="51.0">51</number>
</figureCitation>
, tergite 
<number box="[609,624,352,378]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" value="9.0">9</number>
being slightly smaller than in the drawing provided in 
<bibRefCitation author="Jervis" box="[1274,1432,352,378]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" refString="Jervis, M. A. (1992) A taxonomic revision of the pipunculid fly genus Chalarus Walker, with particular reference to the European fauna. Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society, 105, 243 - 352." type="journal article" year="1992">
Jervis (
<number box="[1359,1423,352,378]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" value="1992.0">1992</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
. The ovipositor is very similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[533,715,392,417]" class="Insecta" family="Pipunculidae" genus="Chalarus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="holosericeus">
<emphasis box="[533,715,392,417]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">C. holosericeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but smaller on the whole (see Jervis’ drawings for 
<taxonomicName box="[1312,1435,392,417]" class="Insecta" family="Pipunculidae" genus="Chalarus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="zyginae">
<emphasis box="[1312,1435,392,417]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">C. zyginae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[200,348,432,457]" class="Insecta" family="Pipunculidae" genus="Chalarus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="perplexus">
<emphasis box="[200,348,432,457]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">C. perplexus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to get an idea of the ratio). Also, tergite 
<number box="[820,835,432,458]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" value="9.0">9</number>
is gently and evenly bent. Its known host species is 
<taxonomicName box="[151,312,472,497]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Zygina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="suavis">
<emphasis box="[151,312,472,497]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Zygina suavis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
